{"question": "Who has to file a Canadian income tax return?", "answer": "You have to file a return if the Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) asks you to, if you owe tax or want to claim a refund, or if you want to receive certain benefits or credits. CRA explains that you must file when you dispose of capital property, repay Old Age Security or Employment Insurance benefits, withdraw funds under the Home Buyers’ Plan or Lifelong Learning Plan, have more than $3,500 in net self‑employment income (to pay EI premiums), incurred a non‑capital loss you want to apply to another year, or want to transfer unused tuition credits to someone else【260661536183006†L53-L103】.", "source_section": "CRA – Who has to file a return", "source_url": ["https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/about-your-tax-return/who-has-file-return.html"], "tags": ["filing-requirements", "tax-return"], "difficulty": "basic"}

{"question": "What are the deadlines for filing the 2025 income tax return and RRSP contributions?", "answer": "For the 2025 tax year, the RRSP contribution deadline is 2 March 2026. The CRA’s key dates page states that personal income tax returns for most individuals are due by 30 April 2026, with taxes owed payable by the same date. If you or your spouse or common‑law partner is self‑employed, you can file your return by 15 June 2026, but any tax balance must still be paid by 30 April 2026【196864145142724†L59-L66】.", "source_section": "CRA – Important dates for individuals", "source_url": ["https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/key-dates.html"], "tags": ["deadlines", "rrsp", "tax-return"], "difficulty": "basic"}

{"question": "Who is eligible for the GST/HST credit?", "answer": "To be eligible for the GST/HST credit you must be a resident of Canada for the month before and the month in which the CRA makes the payment, be at least 19 years old (or have a spouse, common‑law partner or child), and file a tax return even if you have no income. The CRA’s eligibility page notes that you must meet all conditions and that high‑income individuals will not receive a credit【360748768990294†L60-L109】.", "source_section": "CRA – GST/HST credit eligibility", "source_url": ["https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/child-family-benefits/gst-hst-credit/who-eligible.html"], "tags": ["gst-hst", "benefits", "eligibility"], "difficulty": "basic"}

{"question": "What are the eligibility criteria for the Canada Child Benefit (CCB)?", "answer": "The Canada Child Benefit is available to parents or guardians who live with and care for a child under 18 years of age, are primarily responsible for the child’s upbringing, and are residents of Canada. You or your spouse or common‑law partner must be a Canadian citizen, permanent resident, protected person, temporary resident (after 18 months in Canada), or an individual registered under the Indian Act. CRA states that all these criteria must be met for each child【638520317449984†L60-L121】.", "source_section": "CRA – Canada Child Benefit eligibility", "source_url": ["https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/child-family-benefits/canada-child-benefit/who-apply.html"], "tags": ["benefits", "ccg", "child-care"], "difficulty": "basic"}

{"question": "Who can claim the Canada Workers Benefit (CWB)?", "answer": "The Canada Workers Benefit is a refundable tax credit for low‑income workers. According to CRA, you may claim it if you earn working income and your family’s net income is below the threshold for your province or territory, you are a resident of Canada for the entire year, and you are at least 19 years old (or live with a spouse/common‑law partner or a child). You cannot claim the credit if you were a full‑time student for more than 13 weeks (unless you have an eligible dependant), were confined to a prison for more than 90 days, or are an officer or family member of a diplomat【979464762390153†L74-L118】.", "source_section": "CRA – Canada Workers Benefit eligibility", "source_url": ["https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/canada-workers-benefit/who-eligible.html"], "tags": ["cwb", "credits", "low-income"], "difficulty": "basic"}

{"question": "Can I claim home office expenses when working from home?", "answer": "You may claim home office expenses under the detailed method if your employer requires you to work from home (this can be written or verbal), you pay expenses related to your work space, and one of two conditions applies: you work from home more than 50 % of the time for at least four consecutive weeks, or you use the workspace exclusively to earn employment income and regularly meet clients there. CRA notes that you need a signed Form T2200 or T2200S from your employer, and you cannot claim expenses reimbursed by the employer【77737359126623†L79-L160】.", "source_section": "CRA – Work‑space‑in‑the‑home expenses (detailed method)", "source_url": ["https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/about-your-tax-return/tax-return/completing-a-tax-return/deductions-credits-expenses/line-22900.html"], "tags": ["deductions", "home-office", "employment"], "difficulty": "basic"}

{"question": "What is the 2026 Tax‑Free Savings Account (TFSA) contribution limit and what happens if I over‑contribute?", "answer": "The 2026 TFSA annual dollar limit is $7,000. CRA explains that your contribution room is the sum of the current year’s dollar limit, unused room from previous years and withdrawals made in earlier years, and your new room is added on 1 January each year. The agency warns that you should track your own contributions because its TFSA records may not be up to date until the spring, and if you contribute more than your available room, a tax is charged on the excess【36626179507376†L69-L92】.", "source_section": "CRA – TFSA contribution room", "source_url": ["https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/tax-free-savings-account/calculating-contribution-room.html"], "tags": ["tfsa", "savings", "contribution-limit"], "difficulty": "basic"}